<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?><api:response xmlns:api="http://www.symplectic.co.uk/publications/api"><api:version uri="https://mypublications.shef.ac.uk/" elements-version="6.17.0.4095" schema-version="6.13" product-name="myPublications"/><api:request href="https://mypublications.shef.ac.uk:8091/secure-api/v6.13/publications/743577"/><api:result><api:object category="publication" id="743577" last-affected-when="2024-05-01T07:27:17.603+01:00" last-modified-when="2022-11-10T14:14:01.45+00:00" href="https://mypublications.shef.ac.uk:8091/secure-api/v6.13/publications/743577" created-when="2015-05-22T15:55:19.417+01:00" type-id="4" type-display-name="Conference proceedings paper" type="conference"><api:privacy-level>Public</api:privacy-level><api:privacy-level-locked>false</api:privacy-level-locked><api:ever-approved>true</api:ever-approved><api:reporting-date-1>2014-09-07</api:reporting-date-1><api:allow-type-switching>true</api:allow-type-switching><api:records><api:record format="native" id="1311946" source-id="7" source-name="scopus" source-display-name="Scopus" id-at-source="2-s2.0-84953240978" last-modified-when="2020-09-02T21:03:06.067+01:00"><api:citation-count>0</api:citation-count><api:native><api:field name="abstract" type="text" display-name="Abstract"><api:text>Human listeners routinely and unconsciously attune themselves to the reverberation characteristics of their acoustic environment. Experiments by Watkins [J. Acoust. Soc. Am. 118, 249-262 (2005)] and Longworth-Reed et al. [J. Acoust. Soc. Am. 125, EL13-EL19 (2009)] have suggested, however that this process breaks down when the time-direction of reverberation is reversed. This finding is of interest since it is not predicted by intelligibility standards based on the room's modulation transfer characteristic. While Longworth-Reed and colleagues measured a relatively slow room adaptation effect, Watkins found fast-acting compensatory effects within individual utterances. The generality of Watkins' finding remains to be tested, however, since it involved categorical perception of words distinguished by a single consonant cue. The current paper generalises Watkins' experiment by analysing confusions among unvoiced stop-consonants in read speech from multiple talkers, using semantically unpredictable test syllables embedded in short sentences. When the speech precursor was reverberated at a consistent distance with the test item, the accuracy of consonant identification was governed by the time-direction of reverberation in the precursor. The forward condition promoted compensation for the effects of reverberation, indicating a rapid monaural calibration of the listener to the room condition experienced. Under time-reversed reverberation, however, listeners no longer appeared to derive any benefit from a consistently reverberated speech precursor. Finally we describe a computational model in which sensitivity to the room condition was achieved via an efferent auditory pathway that regulated auditory nerve firing based on an estimate of reverberant decay. The model reproduced the essential features of the human listener data.</api:text></api:field><api:field name="authors" type="person-list" display-name="Authors"><api:people><api:person><api:links><api:link type="elements/user" id="9781" href="https://mypublications.shef.ac.uk:8091/secure-api/v6.13/users/9781"/></api:links><api:last-name>Beeston</api:last-name><api:initials>AV</api:initials><api:first-names>AV</api:first-names><api:separate-first-names><api:first-name>A</api:first-name><api:first-name>V</api:first-name></api:separate-first-names><api:addresses><api:address iso-country-code="GB"><api:line type="organisation">The University of Sheffield</api:line><api:line type="city">Sheffield</api:line><api:line type="country">United Kingdom</api:line></api:address></api:addresses><api:identifiers><api:identifier scheme="scopus-author-id">42061033200</api:identifier></api:identifiers></api:person><api:person><